IN SIZING UP the risks of stock-market investments, there's probably no starting place better than "beta." But investors better not ignore its limitations, either
The beta of the broad market, typically defined as the Standard & Poor's 500-stock index, is always 1.0.So a stock with a beta of 0.5 is half as volatile, one at 1.5 is 50% more volatile, and so on
Cautious investors should generally go with stocks that have low betas.Go with high-beta stocks to get the biggest payoff from a bet on a bull market. Remember, though, that beta also has important limitations
Beta figures are widely available and easy to interpret.that beta also has important limitations
There is risk that is not associated with market moves, and the beta doesn't tell you the magnitude of that
and the beta doesn't tell you the magnitude of that.beta doesn't measure the company- and industry-specific risk associated with an individual stock
That "business" risk is very significant for an investor with only a few stocks, but it virtually disappears in a large and well-diversified portfolio
In particular, beta doesn't measure the company- and industry-specific risk associated with an individual stock.Beta is also a poor indicator of the risk in stock groups that march to their own drummer
Beta is also a poor indicator of the risk in stock groups that march to their own drummer.the prices of gold and other precious-metals stocks shoot up and down, but the stocks tend to have low betas because their moves are not market-inspired
In particular, the prices of gold and other precious-metals stocks shoot up and down, but the stocks tend to have low betas because their moves are not market-inspired
but the stocks tend to have low betas because their moves are not market-inspired
In reality it's very volatile, but the movements are not because of market movements
