when an institution, such as Citibank or Sears, Roebuck & Co., takes a pool of credit-card or other receivables and sells them to a specially created trust.The trust then issues securities -- generally due in five years or less -- that are underwritten by Wall Street brokerage firms and offered to investors
Issues typically come with "credit enhancements," such as a bank letter of credit, and thus have received high credit ratings
