ONE DAY Carl Barrett of Mobile, Ala., was raking some sycamore leaves, but the rake kept riding up over the piles
The harder he tried to push them into large piles, the closer he came to breaking the rake and straining his back. So Mr. Barrett, then vice president of the Alabama Steamship Association, took a steel-toothed garden rake and taped it to the underside of a leaf rake about nine inches up
His crude device worked: The lower teeth gathered the leaves into a pile, while the higher, harder teeth moved the top of the pile.Now incorporated into a polypropylene rake, the four-inch prongs, or "wonderbars," also are supposed to aid in picking up leaves
